# "data models for life:"
a pseudo-research paper on the study of complexity and meaning

- "linear trees:" folders are not the issue, they are containers
- "relevance activactes association" based on where you are in time and space, you have access to a nearby constellation of points
- "focus is the sculptor of importance" essentially we have a small ray of focus, and a peripheral vision of context. this means that only one thing matters at a time, but many things in the surrounding are necessary to understand why that one thing matters.
- "association is procedural organization:" the mind works by association, find ways to model the system so that association and discovery are the drivers. 
- "relevance hops" if memories and ideas, data and information are like stars in a field, then the constellations and networks they form are strengthened or weakened by relevance and usage. the more you remember something, the more you use that network, the stronger it becomes. this is essentially how memory works and is itself essential for higher order thinking... i think it's what sepearates us human beings from most animals on the planet... it doesn't make us better than them... it just means we're more complicated lol.
- "complexity increases usefulness but bandwidth as a side effect." not much to say about this other than complexity is a natural scaling of anythign in life that becomes useful or multi-faceted. the challenge is really how we manage our energy across the networks of complexity...
- "wormholes are where context consolidates" arguably the most complex idea... now it would be severly limiting if you could only access nearby constellations of memories and knowledge at a given time. you'd have to jump between related but not relevant memories and ideas before you got to the far off node in the system. wormholes compress both time and space to essentially skip the "relanavce hopping" so that you could... for example... think of a solution to a problem that draws from a completely opposite part of the system, and yet, they are connected. this doesn't mean you've travelled across half the universe and chained a star... infact, it makes those "relevance hops" compressed through that time and space in a way... so that instead of creating a pointlessly long linear  highway between your current idea and the solution, you are instead lighting up that same path in the network... not sure if i explained this correctly... infact i think this concept comes from real neuroscience... "hopfield networks" or something